{"/service/ndnp/ndhi/batch_ndhi_almont_ver01/data/sn88076741/00295863614/1907110101/0796.xml":{"full_text":"5W, 'vJ\nJiv\nA 5?\n1 Itvtjr\n-J', \"V**'\n/i\nEf\nS^\nf?\nF. A. Vatdwell.\nCounty\nCom'rs'\ni',\n,rt~!\nW\n&v\n\"W\n\u2022f Ef\nIT/V'\nf'vx\nk. \"f\n[:j?\nWi\n4*\nNOT CONSTITUTIONAL\nLast Sunday's Herald gives the fol\nlowing clear explanation, and to a cer\ntain extent the Pioneer Express stands\ncorrected.\n\"The pledge provided for in any prim\nary election law is pledge for those can\ndidates who are -voted for at the primary\nelection. The primary election is for the\npurpose of choosing the candidates of\npolitical parties. A man who is not a\nmember of a party cannot be voted for\nat a primary election, and need not be,\n.as he is a candidate simply as an indi\nvidual citizen. Under the old system\n\"the political panties selected their candi\ndates at conventions, and independent\ncandidates were ^nominated by petition\nas such. Under the new system the\nprimary election \u00abimply takes the place\nof a party convention. Party candidates\nare nominated there. Independent can\ndidates may be nominated by petition as\nindividuals, as before.\nThat is what the Pioneer Express\nmeant to say, that an independent hay\ning no party eannot get on a primary\nballot at all. But as the Herald says,\nonly party candidates can be nominated\nat the primaries. Now, if the Herald\nwill kindly give us aa equally clear defi\nnition of the difference between a party\nman and an independent We should feel\nmuch enlightened. Legally, the voter\nat a primary must be a Democrat, a\nRepublican, or a \"five per cent\" by\n\"affiliation.\" We presume that the fel\nlow that don't affiliate is an independ\nent and consequently has no business\nwith the primary election either as a\nvoter or candidate. That's simple enough\nif sombody will only tell us what ''affili\nate\" means in this connection.\nFor instance, say there were twenty\nDemocrat candiates for different offices\non the regular election ballot and twen\nty Republican candidates for the same\noffices respectively, and the voter, as\nwould be his legal right, voted for ten\nDemocratic nominees and ten Republi\ncan nominees \u2014with which party does\nhe \"affiliate\" or is he an independent?\nIs '^affiliation\" a matter of mind or\nV,v3s'\nCan a man who \"affiliates\" with the\nRepublican party in his mind, blit votes\nthe whole of the Democratic ticket, still\nbe a Republican?\nOf course thesp latter questions are\nof the same piece, but are put in slights\nly different form to get at the meaning a\nUtUe0uredinrly.^|\u00b0,\nTh.e Herald (^la attention tb andther\nfact in thia conneofyn, and questions\nto\nThe Bank of Ottawa\nHead .Office, Ottawa* Ontario\nCAPITAL (paid up) $3,000,000.\nRest and Undivided Profits $3,236,512.\nA General Banking Business*\nVour business is invited\nEmerson Branch.A-2aA\u00a3\u00a3.an\nOFFICIAL PAPER OF CITY\nAIND COUNTY.\nrasm&cs. \u00aba.oo\nG.\ntJ'S\n6.\nCourt\n'Thompson.\nVABDWBU ft THOMPSON.\nOfficial Directory\nSenators I an\n(P McCuniber\n'\u2022U ~S Represen-i Thos Marshall\nitatives 1 A 3rontm\n(Governor\u2014John Burke\nLieutenant Governor\u2014-K S iLewis\n^Secretary of State\u2014Alfred Blaisdell\n\u2022State Treasurer\u2014A (Peterson\nState Auditor\u2014H I Holmes\n.Attorney General\u2014IT McCue\nRailroad Com-j\nmissioners fi^ Weetby\nSupt of Pub Inst\u2014W X, Stock well\nCom of Insurance-iE -Cooper\n\u2022Com Asrr Je Labor\u2014W Gilbreath\n.Judger of Supreme'.!?\nE Moriran\n'{.B3\n\"JiFisk\n:F Spalding\nSTATE SENATORS\n1st Dist\u2014Judson fcaMoure, Pembina\n'2nd Dist\u2014F A Halliday. Crystal\nREPRESENTATIVES\nW Watts, Xeroy\n1st District Walter \\Welford, Neclie\n(Joseph Morln, Neclie\nI'E HiRes^ameyer Cav'r\n2nd Districts John Johnson, Gardar\nGanssle, St Thomas\nTudsre 7th ud. Dist\u2014!W Kneeshaw\nCOUNTYiOFFlCIALS\nStates Attorney\u2014'M'Brynjolfson\nClerk of Court\u2014Geo Peterson\nSheriff\u2014Geo Roadliouse\nAuditor\u2014YYm. W- Felson\nTreasurer\u2014Elis Xhorwaldson\nRegister of Deeds\u2014John Gill\nCounty Judire\u2014tH 'Vick\nSupt of Schools\u2014F Slierarts\nSurveyor\u2014F E Hebert\nCoroner\u2014Dr W Brown\nPublic Administrator\u2014T Shaw\n1st\u2014F .C -Myrick, Pem.bina\n2nd\u2014S Siifurdson, Gardar'\n3rd\u2014rAdam Norton, Caval'r\n4th\u2014J N HotKap, Neche\n,5th\u2014'Wm BUrwoo'd.St Tho's\nVOL. XXIX. PEMBINA, N. FRIDAY, NOV\n8AVI Mas DCP'T\nInterest a 1\nlowed on de\nposits of ($1.)\nand upwards\nand added to\nthe account 4\ntimes a year.\nthe constitutionality of compelling a\ncandidate to take oath that he will sup\nport the nominee for the senate chosen\nat the primaries- It thinks that a can\ndidate should have the right to run\nwithout pledging himself if he wants to.\nIn this we agree bnt also think that if\nthe law had left that out, still the legis\nlator would have voted for the nominee\nof the primary just the same as do the\nelectors of the president in the electorial\ncollege\nBut if the primary law shoifld be de\nclared unconstitutional\u2014it is one of the\nrather strange things, that the parties\ncould go ahead and do practically all the\nthings therein provided, without any\nlaw, except that they would have to\nprovide their own voting machinery.\nAnd again, even under the present law,\nthere is nothing to hinder the parties\nholding caucus and convention just as\nthey used to do, and by a little maneu\nvering get the names of their nominees\non the ballots.\nOr, they can just lie still, and the com\nmittee of five can put in the names of\nthe nominees at half the regular price.\nThe primary law here has run up a\ngainst the same difficulty that the Her\nald will do if it attempts to define an\nindependent as distinguished from a\npartisan. The first thing to define is\n\"party\"\u2014and we make bold to say that\nit is an impossibility to'make a legal de\nfinition.\nAnd yet this is the whole foundation\non which the primary law and its regu\nlations are built\u2014and where it fails\nwhen put to the test of constitutionality.\nHow can law be made to regulate' and\ngovern that which Jias no legal exist\nence? What is a party\nTHE HARVESTER TRUST.\nA great deal has been written and\nand said about the \"Harvester Trust.\"\nSome of which is true, some false, but\nthat they are fast gaining control of the\nmarket and compelling all to bow to\ntheir dictate can not be denied. It is\nnever well for one great combination to\ndestroy all strong competitors for trouble\nis sure to follow. One who thinks on\nthese matters can but stop and ponder\nas to what the future offers. The editor\nef the American Cooperative Journal\nafter visiting the great Iowa State Fair\nand looking at this class of exhibits com\nments thus:\nThere was, however one exhibit, that\ntaught a lesson it was not there to teach,\nthat left imprinted on the thinking mind\nan impression it was not intended to\nconvey.\nThe magnificent exhibit of the Inter\nnational Harvester Company, compris\nas it did almost every implement used\nby man, was an object lesson of modern\ntrust methods, the intelligent observer\nwill not soon forget.\nHoused beneath that great canvas was\neverything a man might need in the im\nplement line. There were automobiles\nand engines, harvesters and mowers,\nrakes, spreaders, shredders, wagons and\ncountless other machines all controlled\nby one concern.\nSome bore Deering labels, \u00a3ome had\nMcCormick tags, some were made in\nMilwaukee, some in Ohio, some in Chi\ncago. They represented the output of a\nscore of factories gathered under one\nmanagement for one purpose, to control\nthe machine business, not only of the U.\nS., but of the entire world and grouped\ntogetheir on the fair grounds was an ob\nject lesson of their'success. If they de\nsired to show the farmer how completely\nthey have succeeded they could have\nadopted no better way.\nThe admirer of Deering machinery\nsaw it housed under the same roof with\nMcCormick and Osborne and Milwaukee\noutfits. No one bothered to explain the\nsuperior points of one or tell the wea\npoints of the other, it mattered nvt which\nmachine was sold and which ror. ined\nOne dealer might bdy a car load -f Mc\nCormick binders, another a lot, 1 of\n^Deetfng'fi, still another a load dJ \u00abhe\nMilwaukee, or the Osborne's, but the\nIchecks\nbills were all figured by one man, the\nor notes made out to one concern.\nmm\nNo more abominable outrage was ever\nplotted against the grain growers of the\nworld. While the honest bread growers\nof the grain belt states were tilling their\nfarms, a crowd of men whose fortunes\nwere made from those same tillers of the\nsoil were deliberately organizing a mon\nopoly to control the output of every im\nplement factory of the United States,\nand now when they so nearly control\nthem what have they done? Systemat\nically raised the price of every imple\nment they eontrol and the farmer pays\nthe bill.\nRecently a move was made to investi\ngate its methods and we predict that if\nthe curtain is rolled back from the\nscenes there will be presented another\nview of modern industry no less nauseat\ning than was the inner view of the meat\ntrust and the grain combine.\nAnd some day in the near future a\nman will demand that his state shall es\ntsblish a plant for the manufacture of\ngrain implements when he does there\nwill come the cry of socialist, anarchist,\nprison labor the hired mouthpieces of\nthis unhofy combination will assail him\nfrom press and platform, but the farmer\nof the middle west will do well to listen\nand having listened ponder over the so\nlution of one of the most vital questions\ntoday before the American people. It\nmeans more to the farmer than tariff\nschedules or foreign policies and they\nshould demand that steps be taken to\nrid the country of the evil\u2014give them\nwhat Texas did.\u2014The North Dakota\nParmer.\n[Note:\u2014The inquiry referred to in the\nabove article it a bill introduced in the\nU. S. senate requiring an investigation of\nthe Harvester trust, and introduced by\nHon. H. C, Hansbrough of this state.]\nALMOST A FINANCIAL PANIC\nDuring the\" last ten days the country\nhas been standing on the verge of a\nfinancial panic. If it had depended on\nWall Street alone there would have been\nmany failures. But money has gradual\nly tightened up and the stringency has\nbeen felt in the west.\nOn Monday the Duluth board of trade\nshut up shop for the time being and the\nMinneapolis board while open was not\ndoing .any buying. In both places ar\nriving cars of grain were being placed in\nterminal elevators and storage tickets\nbeing taken.\nOf course this stoppage of buying af\nfected the prices of grain in local mar\nkets to considerable extent, and they\nhave been rapidly falling.\nOn the other hand, the panicky condi\ntions are said to be gradually improving\nand confidence is being restored. Very\nfew large failures have resulted and sev\neral \"runs\" on great financial institu\ntions have been withstood without the\nbanks closeing their doors.\nAs to real value of grain, the conditions\nall point to the late prices, except per\nhaps barley, as being the legitimate re\nsults of supply and demand. Europe\nhas been calling on our markets all along\nfor wheat to supply their demands.\nThis is one reason there has been and\nwili be no panic. It takes money to buy\nwheat this year and that wheat money\nfrom Europe will soon have its effect on\nthe grain and financial centers. A pe\nculiarty of this year's crop is that it\ntakes much more money than usual to\nhandle it on account of the high prices,\nand this is one reason why it is so hard\nfor the elevator men and western ban\nkers to get the necessary cash to buy\nthe grain.\nThe barley crop alone this year must\nhave absorbed an immense sum of mon\ney that is usually paid out for wheat.\nWe doubt if barley gets back on its high\npedestal again, but barley at 30 to 35\ncents at this time would seem to us to\nbe good property to .hold. Under the\ncircumstances surrounding it, the com\nparatively small decrease in price, is\nproof positive of its actual and probable\nfuture value.\nWHO CHOOSES THE SENATORS?\nThe constitution of the United States\nsays:\u2014\nArt. II. The house of representatives\nshall be composed of members chosen\nevery second year by the people.\nArt. III. The senate, of the United\nStates shall be composed of two senators\nfrom each state chosen by the legisla\nture thereof.\nThe primary law of North Dakota\nsays:\u2014\nSec. 13. The candidate receiving the\nhighest number of votes at euch primary\nelection shall be the nominee of his par\nty for the office of United States senator\nat the succeeding session of the legisla\nture.\nSec. 4. The petitions of all candidate^\n-V^7, vc,\"\\ V-'s-fF*^\nI\nfor members of the legislative assembly\nshall contain the following pledge: I do\nobligate myself I will sup\nport and vote for that candidate for\nUnited States senator of the party which\nI am a member, who has received a ma\njority of such party vote at the primary\nelection.\nThe U. S. constitution says that rep\nresentatives shall be elected by the\n\"people\", that senators shall be elected\nby the \"legislature\"\u2014and the primary\nlaw of North Dakota says as above.\nIn our discussion of some of the in\nconsistencies of the primary law in this\nissue we do not want it understood that\nwe do not favor the choice of the U. S.\nsenators by the people. We think with\nthe Herald that the law has gone too\nfar, and that the same thing could have\nMen done by simply providing any sort\nof plebescite showing the choice of the\nparties, as most legislators would follow\ntljat choice without compulsion.\n?We are in favor of nominating all the\nmjDre important officers by primary vote,\nfor on these officials the people do have\npositive opinions and knowledge of per\nsons but in the fifty or more minor offi\nices on the ballots, the people at large\ncannot have the needed information and\npersonal knowledge for choosing. In\nthis the old convention system in our\nopinion is far better, though we admit\nhas faults of its own.\nWarning\u2014Food Weights\nCIRCULAR NO.\n2.\nThe Food Law in this state requires\nthat all food products and beverages\nshall be labeled to show the true net\nweight (or measure,) t]ie true grade, and\nthe true name and address of the manu\nfacturer or jobber. Therefore, take no\ntice that the provisions of this Law will\nbe strictly enforced.\nOn and after November, 9th, 1907 any\ndealer receiving further consignment of\ncrackers, etc., to be sold in the state\nmust see that the same is properly la\nbel for weight, grade and manufacturer.\nThe National Biscuit Co., through\ntheir attorney, has declined to comply\nwith the provisions of this Law. You\nare therefore, cautioned that the sale of\npackage goods sent out by this or other\nh(fuses and not properly labeled will be\n'contested:\"\n(Signed) E. F. LADD,\nFood Commissioner\nThe fact that the annual enrollment\nat the Minneapolis Business College is\ndouble that of any other#like school in\nthe Northwest proves that this college\nmust be the best. A line to Rugg\nBoyce, 300 Central Ave., brings complete\ninformation.\nWANTED:\u20141000 young men to study\ntelegraphy at the Crookston College.\nThere is a great call for operators and\nbeginning with next spring the railroads\nwill put on about twice as mauy men as\nthey have at the present time. Our last\nyears graduates are now receiving from\n860 to \u00a780 per month. Our teacher is\none of the chief operators on the Great\nNorthern Railway. Send for catalog to\nJ. C. SATHRE,\nCKOOKSTON, MINN.\nNEW CITY MARKET\nWe have opened anew Meat\nMarket in the store room re\ncently occupied by Miss LaBar\nand ask a share of the public\npatronage. We will keep on\nhand everything necessary to\ndie outfit of a first class shop\nand hope by attention to busi\nriess to deserve and-receive your\ncustom.\nRespectfully'\nKERNS& DUNN\nLearn The Barber Trade.\nyiy-^ i, iHQ7.\nO\nGreat demand for\nBarbers\u2014Big Wages\nEasy worli\u2014Few weeks\nCompletes Expert In\nstructions\u2014Tuois given\nDiplomas granted\nFor snort time Illust\nrated Catalog Explain\ning all\u2014FREE.\nMOHLER BARBER COLLEGE,\n(Established 1893)\n23 NICOLLET AVENUE,\nMinneapolis, Minn.\nBAY STACK\nOOVEBS\niMattMlaf art tntab\nitoferMtaioaatl\nkMMCuiu\n1\n4\no.\n2 S&\n0 I\n9\nHENEMAN\nSAYS!\nGood Eastern Apples\nThis year will not be very plenti\nful but he expects part of a car of\nFANCY EASTERN APPLES\nthis coming week which he ex\npects to sell at about\n$5.25 to $5.50 Per Barrel.\nFancy Western Apples\nat Our Store now at\n$2.15 Per Box.\nWould also call your attention toour\nnew line of\nRugs and Art Squares\nIf you find you are in need\nof one we would be pleas\ned to show you these and\nquote you our low CASH\nprices.\nJOHN HENEMAN\nWE HAVE, THE BEST\nYOU CAN'T BEAT US\nWe also have\nWall Paper\nGlass\nPutty\nYarnisii\nJapalac\nGlass\nPutty\nVarnish\nJapalac\nWhite Lead\nLinseed Oil\nBlood's Paint\nBrushes\nFpvifY 'r\n\nNUMBER\nSchool Books\nTablets\nComposition Books\nInk\nPencils\nErasers\nEverything required in\nSfhnol\nSchool\nAll the time\nHave just received a nice line of Musical\nO Merchandise Accodians, Harmonicas, Pianos etc.\naxxxoooooo\nOur New Fall\nStock of\nDRY GOODS\nHas arrived\nGome in and see them,\nWhether you buy or not.\nFresh groceries and fruit always on hand.\nR. A. Branchaud.\nr\u00ab\n18\nI. !*-V^'f\nf-\nO\nh'\na- luff","height":"26696","width":"19045"}}
